Well, it&#39;s 

    if (walk.Length != 10) return false;

that matters **most**. When checking `10` items only either `foreach` loop or `Count` are *good enough* (technically, `Count` will be nanoseconds behind). But, your `2nd` implemention:

     ...
     return walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;n&quot;) == walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;s&quot;) ... &amp;&amp; walk.Length == 10;

is wrong. Just see, for `walk = new string[2_000_000_000];` you first count `x` and `y` (huge loops, *2 billion* items to check) and *only then* validate `Length`. It should be

     // First check for length
     // Then for items of a (small, 10 items only) array
     return walk.Length == 10 
         &amp;&amp; walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;n&quot;) == walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;s&quot;) 
         &amp;&amp; walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;e&quot;) == walk.Count(x =&gt; x == &quot;w&quot;);

first ensure that the array is short (`10` items only), then loop over it. For a *microoptimization* (let&#39;s win some nanoseconds) I suggest something like this (please, note, there&#39;s no *practical sence* in it)

     public static bool IsValidWalk(string[] walk)
     {
         // Since we have public method we have to validate the input - null == walk
         if (null == walk || walk.Length != 10) 
             return false;

         int x = 0; 
         int y = 0;
   
         // for: we don&#39;t want IEnumerator&lt;int&gt;
         // reverse: comparison with i &gt;= 0 is faster then i &lt; walk.Length
         // Magical constanct 9 instead of walk.Length - 1 makes the code a bit faster 
         for (int i = walk.Length - 1; i &gt;= 0; --i)      
         {
             string dir = walk[i];

             if (dir == &quot;n&quot;) ++x; 
             else if (dir == &quot;s&quot;) --x;
             else if (dir == &quot;e&quot;) ++y;
             else if (dir == &quot;w&quot;) --y;
         }
 
         // &amp; is just a multuplication, when &amp;&amp; will be turned into JZ (JNZ) isntructions
         return x == 0 &amp; y == 0;
     }

If you&#39;re inclined towards using shorter code, e.g. LINQ, here is an alternate idea that should perform better than your version:

    walk.Length == 10 &amp;&amp;
    walk.Sum(x =&gt; (x == &quot;n&quot; ? 1  : (x == &quot;s&quot; ? -1 : 0))) == 0 &amp;&amp;
    walk.Sum(x =&gt; (x == &quot;n&quot; ? 1 : (x == &quot;s&quot; ? -1 : 0))) == 0

